‚ÄãCard 1: The "Pipeline" (Incoming Requests)
‚ÄãThis is your active card. It‚Äôs the only one that requires quick decision-making.
‚ÄãWhat it does: It acts as a inbox specifically for new student bookings.
‚ÄãThe User Flow: A tutor sees a red notification dot here, clicks it, and sees a simple list. They can accept or decline a request immediately.
‚ÄãWhy it‚Äôs efficient: It saves the tutor from digging through emails or a general chat inbox to find out who wants a lesson.




‚ÄãCard 2: The "Agenda" (My Schedule)
‚ÄãThis is the operational card. It‚Äôs for tutors who are already "booked and busy."
‚ÄãWhat it does: It shows a focused view of today and tomorrow.
‚ÄãThe Logic: It ignores history and long-term future. It strictly tells the tutor: "You have a CSC01A1 session in 2 hours at the Library."
‚ÄãThe Utility: It includes the "Start Lesson" button here, so it‚Äôs the primary workspace during an actual tutoring session.




‚ÄãCard 3: The "Presence" (Profile & Availability)
‚ÄãThis is the management card. It controls how the tutor appears to the world.
‚ÄãWhat it does: It houses the "Online/Offline" toggle and the weekly availability grid.
‚ÄãThe Strategy: Instead of burying availability in a deep settings menu, putting it on the main hub allows a tutor to quickly "Go Offline" if they have a sudden exam or personal emergency.
‚ÄãLess Work: It also shows the modules they are currently "Certified" to teach, allowing them to add or remove subjects based on their confidence level.




‚ÄãCard 4: The "Vault" (Combined Analytics & Records)
‚ÄãThis is the passive card. It‚Äôs the "simple data" powerhouse we discussed.
‚ÄãThe Design: This is the only card that is purely informative. No buttons to click (except "Download"), no graphs to decipher.
‚ÄãThe Content: It‚Äôs a tabbed ledger. One tab for History (who, when, where), one tab for Ratings (the "vibe check" from students), and one tab for Stats (the total hours count).
‚ÄãThe Purpose: Tutors only open this when they need to check their progress or download a service transcript for their CV. It stays out of the way until it's needed.




‚Äã1. Home (The Hub)
‚ÄãIcon: A house or grid icon.
‚ÄãPurpose: This brings them back to the 2x2 grid we just planned. It is the "reset" button.
‚ÄãWhy: Since the cards contain the main actions (Accepting requests, starting lessons), they need a quick way back to that dashboard.




‚Äã2. Inbox (Chat)
‚ÄãIcon: A speech bubble.
‚ÄãPurpose: Direct access to the list of ongoing conversations with students.
‚ÄãLogic: While Card 1 (Requests) is for new bookings, the Inbox tab is for communication. A student might message saying, "I'm running 5 mins late," or "Can we meet at a different table?" The tutor needs to be able to reach this from anywhere in the app with one tap.




‚Äã3. Alerts (Activity Feed)
‚ÄãIcon: A bell.
‚ÄãPurpose: A simple, chronological list of things that happened while they were away.
‚ÄãContent: "Student X cancelled for tomorrow," "Admin verified your hours for MAT1A01," or "New rating received."
‚ÄãWhy: It acts as a "log" so they don't have to go hunting through the Vault (Card 4) to see recent changes.



‚Äã4. Support (The Lifeline)
‚ÄãIcon: A lifebuoy or "ticket" icon.
‚ÄãPurpose: Reporting issues (Student no-shows, technical bugs, or campus safety).
‚ÄãWhy: Tutors are often working alone in libraries or labs. Having a dedicated tab for support makes them feel backed by the university. It‚Äôs better than hiding it inside a profile menu.




‚Äã5. Account (Mini-Profile)
‚ÄãIcon: A person or gear icon.
‚ÄãPurpose: Logout, app settings, and basic account details.
‚ÄãNote: We keep this separate from Card 3 (Presence). Card 3 is about teaching (availability/modules); this tab is about the app (security/logout).










